        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> It is easy for me to enhance **-M** so that we can handle all permutations:\r\n> \r\n> 1. Only place legend entries set with **-l**\r\n> 2. Only place legend entries given by _specfile_\r\n> 3. Append legend entries from _specfile_ to those set by **-l**\r\n> 4. Append legend entries set by **-l** to those given by _specfile_\r\n> \r\n> I think those are the possibilities, no?\r\n\r\nI agree, but what's the default behavior when both `-l` and a _specfile_ is used? I actually agree what @ibrewster just said:\r\n\r\n> When I specify a legend specification file, however, I am _explicitly_ saying \"This is what I want my legend to be\", and as such I was expecting the specification file to override the labels, and found it surprising when that didn't happen.\r\n\r\nSo my expectations are:\r\n\r\n- `-l` alone: use the hidden legend entries\r\n- _specfile_ alone: use the legend entries in the _specfile_\r\n- both `-l` and a _specfile_\r\n  - without **-M** (default behavior): using _specfile_ because it's _explicitly_ set\r\n  - **-M***option*: deal with all possibilities",
